<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Fri, 7 Jul 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Bloomberg, 7 Jul 2006 [edited]
<http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601100&sid=aC5st1TiLuwc&refer=germany>

Spain, Europe's biggest tourism destination by revenue, confirmed its
1st case of bird flu.
The National Laboratory at Algete near Madrid
found the H5N1 virus in a sample taken from a
grebe [diving waterfowl] found in the province of
Alava, the Agriculture Ministry today said on its Web site.
Avian influenza has spread across the European Union, prompting some
consumers to spurn poultry. The World Health Organization has said
there's no risk in eating poultry or eggs that are properly cooked.
The World Tourism Organization said it's safe to travel to countries
that have reported bird flu as long as tourists avoid close contact
with birds.
Spain gets 46 billion euros (USD 59 billion) in revenue a year from
foreign tourists and the industry makes up about 1/10 of gross
domestic product. Most tourists come from the U.K., Germany and
France. Hotel companies such as Sol Melia SA and airlines including
Iberia Lineas Aereas de Espana SA depend on tourism for profit growth.
Germany, Greece, Italy, Hungary, Slovenia and Austria are among
countries that have reported outbreaks, mostly in swans.
Most of the people who have contracted the virus [so far 10 countries
have recorded human cases; none of them in Europe - Mod.AS] handled
infected poultry or came in contact with their excrement.
