[2]
Date: Fri, 7 Jul 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: CBC News, Canada, 7 Jul 2006 [edited]
<http://www.cbc.ca/story/world/national/2006/07/07/avian-spain.html>

A laboratory in Spain has confirmed the country's 1st case of the
H5N1 bird flu, found in a wild bird in the northern province of
Alava, the Agriculture Ministry said on Friday.
The waterfowl, a great crested grebe [Picture at
<http://www.animalpicturesarchive.com/ArchHAN01/1106306471.jpg>], was
picked up in a marsh area outside the city of Vitoria.
The director of the European Centre for Disease Prevention and
Control (ECDC) said Friday that Europe should expect a seasonal
pattern of avian influenza in the coming months and years.
"As long as the virus is endemic in Asia and parts of Africa, it's
quite likely it will reappear in Europe," Zsuzsanna Jakab told a news
conference in Brussels.
Last month, Jakab told an ECDC conference in Athens that migrating
birds are carrying the respiratory disease and Europe "must be
prepared."
Spain is on the route of northern-bound migratory birds from Africa.
