[3]
Date: Fri, 7 Jul 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Inthenews.co.uk, 7 Jul 2006 [edited]
<http://www.inthenews.co.uk/news/news/environment/spain-confirms-first-bird-flu-case-$444256.htm>

Spanish authorities have confirmed the country's 1st case of the
deadly H5N1 strain of bird flu.
A great crested grebe was found dead in the northern province of
Alava, in marshes in Salburua lake near the city of Vitoria.
"The National Reference Laboratory has confirmed a case of highly
pathogenic H5N1 type bird flu," the agriculture ministry said in a
statement.
Spanish vice-president Maria Teresa Fernandez de la Vega has appealed
for calm and advised that the case would not affect people.
A protection zone of 3 km (2 miles) has been set up around the area
where the wild bird was found and up to 10 km from the spot is to be
monitored.
Spanish officials said in 2005, after news that bird flu had spread
to a number of European countries, including France and Romania, that
it was "only a matter of time" before the disease reached Spain,
especially as it is on the northbound migratory route for birds from
Africa.
